3. Useful Shortcuts
Ctrl + C â†’ stop process
Ctrl + Z â†’ pause
Ctrl + L â†’ clear
Tab â†’ autocomplete


*********************************************************************************************
                                        Shell Scripting for DevOps
    --> Shell scripts automate repetitive tasks.  

1. Basic Script Structure
#!/bin/bash
echo "Hello DevOps"

Save as: script.sh
To Run: 
chmod +x script.sh
./script.sh

2. Variables
NAME="DevOps"
echo "Welcome $NAME"

3. Conditional Statements
if [ $1 -gt 10 ]; then
  echo "Value greater than 10"
else
  echo "Value less than or equal to 10"
fi

4. Loops
For Loop:
for i in 1 2 3 4 5
do
  echo "Number $i"
done

While Loop:
count=1
while [ $count -le 5 ]
do
  echo "Count: $count"
  count=$((count+1))
done

5. Functions
hello() {
  echo "Hello from DevOps function!"
}
hello

*********************************************************************************************
                                   Networking Basics for DevOps

--> Networking is essential for AWS, Kubernetes, Docker, CI/CD, and servers.
--> IP Address â€“ Device identifier on a network.
--> Subnet â€“ Divides a network into smaller parts.
--> DNS â€“ Converts names to IPs.
--> Port â€“ Communication channel on a device.
--> Protocol â€“ Rules for network communication.
--> Firewall â€“ Blocks or allows network traffic.
--> Load Balancer â€“ Distributes traffic to servers.
--> VPN â€“ Secure private network connection.
--> SSH Tunnel â€“ Encrypted remote connection.
--> Container Networking â€“ Connects containers/services.

1. Key Networking Concepts
--> IP Address
Identifies devices on a network.

--> Subnet
A smaller portion of a network.

--> DNS
Translates domain into IP.

--> Ports
Identify applications on a machine.

Port	Service
22	SSH
80	HTTP
443	HTTPS
3306	MySQL

2. OSI Model 
--> The OSI (Open Systems Interconnection) Model is a 7-layer framework that standardizes network communication. Each layer has a specific function:

7 â”€ Application      â†’ User interface, applications (HTTP, FTP, SMTP)
6 â”€ Presentation     â†’ Data translation, encryption, compression (SSL, JPEG)
5 â”€ Session          â†’ Manages sessions and connections
4 â”€ Transport        â†’ Reliable/unreliable delivery, flow control (TCP/UDP)
3 â”€ Network          â†’ Routing and logical addressing (IP)
2 â”€ Data Link        â†’ Frames, MAC addresses, error detection (Ethernet)
1 â”€ Physical         â†’ Bits, cables, switches, physical transmission

---------------------------------
Note: DevOps mostly works with:
Layer 4 (TCP/UDP) & Layer 3 (IP)
--------------------------------------
3. Important Commands
--> Connectivity
ping google.com
curl httpbin.org/get
wget url

--> Ports
netstat -tulpn
ss -tulpn

--> DNS
nslookup google.com
dig amazon.com

***************************************************************************************************************************************************************
                                                                      Git Basics
--> Git is the most important tool in DevOps.
--> Git is a distributed version control system, meaning repositories can exist locally and remotely.
--> Tracking Changes â€“ Git keeps a history of all changes, making it easy to revert, compare, or recover previous versions.
--> Branches â€“ Developers can create multiple branches for features, bug fixes, or experiments without affecting the main code.
--> Merging & Conflict Resolution â€“ Changes from different branches can be merged; conflicts are handled manually if needed.
--> Remote Repositories â€“ Git supports collaboration via platforms like GitHub, GitLab, and Bitbucket.
--> Staging Area â€“ The index or staging area allows selective commits, giving control over what changes to record.
--> Fast & Lightweight â€“ Git is optimized for speed and can handle large projects efficiently.
--> Security â€“ Uses SHAâ€‘1 hashing to ensure integrity of commits and history.

1. Configure Git
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "you@example.com"
